<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-508-390  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 508 390.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  August 7 1989 v8 n16 p89(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GSA can review procurement staff before giving OK. (GeneralServices Administration) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dornan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government RegulationGovernment OfficialsEquipment AcquisitionPersonnelUnited States. General Services Administration.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Developments and documents. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GSA Can Review Procurement Staff Before Giving OKandM;In the July 20 delegation of procurement authority for the NavyComputer-Aided Design program (Case KMA-89-0339), the General Servicesadministration established a new precedent.andM;GSA suspended action on the Navy's agency procurement request until theservice supplies detailed information about the people involved in theprocurement.andP;  GSA officials want to know the background of all seniorprogram, technical and contract officials.andP;  Specifically, the Navy mustdetail the officials' experience in similar major ADP procurements, theirresponsibilities, the scope of their authority, the reporting structure andtheir non-CAD responsibilities.andM;In addition, GSA officials want to know the structure of the organizationsthat support these people.andM;GSA has the authority to check the qualifications of agency and organizationpersonnel before delegating procurement authority.andM;Except for agency management reviews, this is the first time GSA has takensuch actions on a specific procurement.andM;GSA is sending a clear message to agencies -- any agency procurement issubject to suspension until GSA conducts a background check on keyprocurement personnel.andM;This counters GSA's original position that procurements would not be delayedwhile acting on an agency procurement request.andP;  GSA had indicated that a DPAwould be granted while conducting a concurrent review.andM;I prefer up-front GSA reviews and decisions before issuing a DPA, rather thanthe concurrent review.andP;  I believe this reduces the possibility of majorredirection later in the procurement process.andM;In any case, agencies should never allow the DPA to be on the critical pathof a procurement, but should process this request concurrently with otheractions.andM;Now more than ever, agencies also must be concerned about the qualificationsof the people involved.andP;  Perhaps agencies should send more people to the GSATrail Boss training class and other courses.andO;</TEXT></DOC>